,Recommended,270880,23709747,"Posted: 22 June, 2016",all,951Jimbo,"American Truck Simulator is a great game with some serious problems.  It's still a classic and loads of fun, but you may find more value in Euro Truck Sim 2.I have a big debate of whether I prefer ATS (American Truck Sim) or ETS2 (Euro Truck Sim 2).  The two games are very similar.  The UI, graphics, and game controls are improved in ATS, but overall the titles are very similar.  ETS2 has a vastly larger world.  As an American, learning and seeing the European countryside is interesting while driving on the California I-5 is objectively not.ProGood Sim, the trucks feel real and the various options allow you to make the game more arcade or more simThe world is fun, I don't know if I would say accurate, but it feels genuine in many ways.  California looks like California, Nevada back country feels like Nevada back countryGraphics are improved, not great, but acceptableSteam workshop modsThe red light tickets are really bad....unfortunately it's very realistic just like the number of pot dispensaries in Bakersfield.ConsPerformance is really bad.  Even on a Haswell i5 and GTX 980 the game really struggles to push out 60fps - and the hardware isn't maxed.  This isn't helped much by reducing the settings.  The game just doesn't run well.  My understanding is that aside from being poorly optimized it's running an old DirectX version.Without Stam Cloud, all of you saves are stored locally.  It means you either need to risk all your progress or go through the trouble of backing you saves up through a 3rd party solution.  If you decide to come back to the game in the future you may not be able to locate your savesThere are not enough vehicles in the game as of June 2016.  This will likely change.  However, with ETS2 the developers just put in truck-look-a-likes until the licenses were secured.  Why wasn't this done in ATS?"
