76561198243946176,Recommended,270880,20968161,"Posted: 5 February, 2016",all,SgtSully,"Love this game. If you enjoy ETS2, this is the game for you. It is a little underwhelming, with only California, Nevada, and the Peterbilt 579 and Kenworth T680. This should change soon, with the state of Arizona being added soon as a free DLC, and the Peterbilt 389 and Kenworth W900 are on their way. The devs have shown us sneak peeks at a International Lonestar, Volvo VNL780, and a Freightliner in the works, and have stated that they will be supporting the game long-term. ATS is not as forgiving for new truck drivers as ETS2, so I would suggest you be extremely careful if this is your first trucking game, as the fines are horrendous. $1000 for speeding, $900 for hitting a car, and $700 for running a red-light. The cops are merciless, and when you only have $1500 to start with, it adds up quickly. I would highly recommend the game if you are like me and love details and eye-candy. The map is beautiful, very detailed with small additions such as skateboarders in parks and workmen at delivery points. The delivery points are much more varied and detailed compared to ETS2. This game does feel like a standalone DLC to ETS2 at this point, but I think that once more content is released it will begin to come into its own. While people are complaining that the whole map is only about the size of two ETS2 UKs, they have failed to note that the map is much more detailed than ETS2. In ETS2, every town looks pretty much the same, while in ATS, there is actually some fun in discovering new towns and cities, they actually look different from one another. I love this game and at $20, it's very reasonably priced, especially with more content to come."
